  pm-pee5,related,"2026-07-06T23:26:29.415Z",null,null
body: "At decades scale the overwhelming majority of a workspace is closed history. Today context assembly either ignores it (losing the recorded knowledge: decisions, learnings, why-nows) or pays full per-item cost to include it. There is no middle representation between 'full item' and 'absent'.\n\nProposal (long horizon, after pm-801d and pm-4k6b): a derived rollup layer, SDK-first.\n- Cluster closed items by natural epoch boundaries (release, epic subtree, time window) into compact summary records: scope, outcome, key decisions/learnings, member-ID list for drill-down.\n- Summaries are DERIVED artifacts, regenerated from source items + history — never mutations of tracked items (no changelog drag, no history noise); stored like other derived indexes (semantic ledger precedent).\n- Context assembly (pm-4k6b knowledge-density signal) and search can return a rollup as a cheap stand-in when the budget cannot afford members, with drill-down via existing get/history.\n- Complements pm-o79o, which handles the DISK/git cost of old data; this handles the TOKEN/context cost. Together they define the aging story for million-item, decades-spanning workspaces.\n\nStart with a spike + design note; the clustering fidelity question (mechanical rollup vs. model-assisted summaries via an extension hook) is explicitly part of the spike."
